Dipole only runs¶

Changing the drift time-scale¶

We run Toast, observe just a dipole map, and inject gain fluctuations with a $5\%$ width on a time-scale of 1 day. I smooth the maps to $1^\circ $ so that large scales are emphasized.

In [66]:
map1  = hp.read_map(field=range(3) , 
                       filename='madam_bmap_001.fits', 
                       verbose=False)
fig=pl.figure(figsize=(15,8))
driftmap1=  hp.smoothing(map_in=map1, fwhm=pl.deg2rad(1.), verbose=False  )
#hp.mollview(  driftmap1 [0], unit='K ', title=r'$  T$  ', sub=131 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap  )
hp.mollview(driftmap1 [1], unit='K ', title=r'$  Q$', sub=132 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap )
hp.mollview(driftmap1 [2], unit='K ', title=r'$U$', sub=133 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap )
cl1=hp.anafast( map1 , lmax=lmax)

Figure 1: We are simply emphasizing the cumulative effect (on a daily scale) of having a mismatch between detA and detB. Notice that a large scale pattern appears on both Q, U maps and the wiggles along the equator

Now, I reduce the drift time-scale to 12 h.

If the gain mismatches are on a shorter time-scale any coherence will be lost: the gain fluctuates too fast and looks as noise. Indeed for an even smaller time-scale 10 min we observe similar structures.

Reducing gain width¶

Now let's keep the time-scale to 24 h and reduce the width of the distribution by an order of magnitude ($0.5 \%$ ). We expect a leakage in the Q and U maps about 1 orders of magnitude smaller than the one in Fig.1

In [73]:
map3  = hp.read_map(field=range(3) , 
                       filename='madam_bmap_003.fits', 
                       verbose=False)
fig=pl.figure(figsize=(15,8))
driftmap3=  hp.smoothing(map_in=map3, fwhm=pl.deg2rad(1.), verbose=False )
#hp.mollview(  driftmap1 [0], unit='K ', title=r'$  T$  ', sub=131 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap  )
hp.mollview(driftmap3 [1], unit='K ', title=r'$  Q$', sub=132 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap)
hp.mollview(driftmap3 [2], unit='K ', title=r'$U$', sub=133 , fig=fig ,cmap=cmap )
cl3=hp.anafast( map3 , lmax=lmax)

We do observe similar stripes as in Fig.1 and more importantly a factor of 10 lower leakage.

Let's check out the power spectra.

In [85]:
fig=pl.figure(figsize=(16, 5))
dicspectra={0:'TT', 1:'EE', 2:'BB', 3:'TE'}
for i in xrange(3): 
    pl.subplot(131 +i )
    pl.title(dicspectra[i])
    pl.loglog(cl1[i,:]*1e12, label = 'Time drift =24 h, width 5% ')
    pl.loglog(cl9[i,:]*1e12, label = 'Time drift =12 h,     " ')
    pl.loglog(cl2[i,:]*1e12, label = 'Time drift =1.5 h,    " ')
    pl.loglog(cl0[i,:]*1e12, label = 'Time drift =10 min,     ""')

    
    
    
    pl.loglog(cl[:,0] ,cl[:,i+1],'k')
    pl.loglog(cl3[i,:]*1e12, alpha=.4, label = 'Time drift =24 h  width=0.5 %')
    
    if i==0:   
        pl.ylabel(r'$C_{\ell} [ \mu K^2 ]$', fontsize=16)
        pl.legend()
    pl.xlabel(r'$ {\ell}  $', fontsize=16)

Figure 2: Power spectra computed from the TQU maps encoding just the Dipole and the leakage into polarization maps. as a reference we show the theoretical CMB power spectra in black. Notice that the smaller is the time-scale of the drift the lower is the amplitude of the residual at large scales, as well as the scatter from a power law.

Figure 3: Power spectra computed from the TQU maps encoding Dipole+CMB T. Similarly to figure 2, and the residual into QU maps is proportional to the width of the gain distribution and for a smaller time-scale of the drift the amplitude of EE and BB power spectra is lower at large scales. TT power spectra are perfectly overlapped, the decrease in power a higher $\ell $ is due to beam effects.
